Q1). Repeat purchase rate (FIND REPEAT CUSTOMER RATE) 
  Calculate percentage of customers who placed more than one order. Return repeat_rate as percent.
  https://fivesql.com/query-practice.html?id=Q33&difficulties=medium&statuses=unsolved&databases=amazon_ecommerce%2Chospital

A1). SELECT ROUND(100.0 * SUM(CASE WHEN order_count > 1 THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) / COUNT(*),2) AS repeat_rate
    FROM (SELECT customer_id, COUNT(*) AS order_count FROM orders GROUP BY customer_id)

Strategy:
first find out order count per person by grouping people by customer id 
then find the repat customer rate by counting people who have more than 1 order count and find the percentage against entire count of people 


Q2). Date time function:
Show all days of the month (1-31) and how many admission_dates occurred on that day. Sort by day with most admissions to least.

A2). SELECT CAST(STRFTIME('%d',admission_date) as integer) as dom, count(*) as ct group by dom order by ct desc, dom asc
      Also to find recent order date for example just do max(order_date) and for oldest order date min(order_date)

Q3). To divide numbers into group. For example weights of prople into groups of 10-20, 20-30 etc etc
     SELECT (FLOOR(weight/10)*10) AS weight_group, COUNT(*) AS total_patients FROM patients GROUP BY weight_group ORDER BY weight_group DESC;

Q4). Give a temporary password to patients who made their first visit.
     SELECT p.patient_id, CAST(p.patient_id AS TEXT) || CAST(LENGTH(p.last_name) AS TEXT) || CAST(strftime('%Y', p.birth_date) AS TEXT)
     AS temp_password FROM patients p JOIN (SELECT patient_id, MIN(admission_date) AS first_adm FROM admissions GROUP BY patient_id) fa
     ON p.patient_id = fa.patient_id;

Q5). Find the employee first name, hire date , salary and the running total of salary.
    select first_name, hire_date, salary, sum(salary) over( order by hire_date rows between  1 preceding and current row )as running_tot
    from employees

Q6). Find running avaerage of salary for two cases:
  i. with the current row and previous row
  ii. current row, previous row and the previous row to it.

    i. Select first_name, hire_date, salary, avg(salary) over(order by hire_date rows between 1 preceding and current rows) as run_avg1 from employees
    ii. Select first_name, hire-date, salary, avg(salary) over(order by hire_date rows between 2 preceding and current rows) as run_av2 from employees

